The annual percentage change in wages has slowly decreased to about 4.98% for September. While it stayed above 5% for the past few months, the increase in average hourly earnings of all workers in the private sector was smaller than this month. From July 2021 to August 2021, it increased by 9 cents. From August 2021 to September 2021, it increased by 16 cents - this larger jump caused the annual percentage change in hourly earnings to drop below 5%. The increase from September 2021 to October 2021 was 19 cents -- an even larger jump. The jump from September 2022 to October 2022 will have to be roughly 29 cents (own calculations), which doesn't seem feasible without some form of government intervention. However, the reason the split is so close is due to the "Median weekly earnings of the nation's 120.2 million full-time wage and salary workers [being] 6.9 percent higher than a year earlier." This excludes the private sector, but if it is any indication of rising wages, then it could be applicable to the private sector. I still believe that the annual percentage change will be between 4% and 5%, however.

The current outbreak of inflation, combined with widespread job vacancies and the difficulties of employers in getting them filled, should combine to drive wages up substantially. On the other hand, US employers have traditionally been quite stingy toward their employees, and reluctant to give them more than the bare minimum necessary. I think it likely that they will have to bow to economic realities and be willing to grant increases in the 2-4% range, but I also think it quite probable that employers will dig in their heels and resist more generous increases.

The world wide covid crisis will continue to drive inflation for goods. The challenges in the US will continue to suppress work force participation. The potential workers are seeing they have the upper hand, and feel taken advantage of, and so will force employers to pay up.

This is heavily linked to inflation. When you consider US CPI is running at 6.2 right now (https://tradingeconomics.com/united-states/inflation-cpi) and has been above 5 since May it seems unlikely that this will drawback on it's own over the next few months (annualised rate should start to stabilise or decrease from the new year as the 'lower' inflation months still in the last 12 months have less impact) but the Fed should start to reduce QE/raise rates by mid-next year. It's not clear that raising interest rates would prevent price inflation immediately but it would make borrowing more costly and might stem rising wages.
